'''Donold B. Lourie''' (1899 <U+2013> 1990) was an American businessman, government official, and [[college football]] player. He served for many years as the president of the [[Quaker Oats Company]], and held various other executive positions there and for several other businesses. President [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] appointed Lourie to a position in the [[United States Department of State|State Department]], and he served in that capacity for one year. Lourie attended [[Princeton University]] where he was a star [[quarterback]], and he was named a consensus [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] as a junior. Lourie was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] in 1974.

==Early life==
Lourie was born on August 22, 1899 in {{city-state|Decatur|Alabama}}. He grew up in {{city-state|Peru|Illinois}} where he attended [[LaSalle-Peru High School]].<ref name=hof>[http://www.collegefootball.org/famersearch.php?id=20046 Member Biography: Don Lourie], College Football Hall of Fame, retrieved July 17, 2009.</ref> He then attended boarding school at the prestigious [[Phillips Exeter Academy]]. He played [[high school football|football]] there, and in his junior season in 1916, scored the winning [[touchdown]] against his school's [[Exeter<U+2013>Andover rivalry|"ancient rival"]], [[Phillips Academy|Andover]]. On the first play in the fourth quarter, he went around the left [[end (American football)|end]] to rush 33 yards for the game's only score.<ref>[http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9901EEDB1F3FE233A2575AC1A9679D946796D6CF EXETER HUMBLES ITS ANCIENT RIVAL; Wins Fourth Consecutive Victory Over Andover Through Lourie's Touchdown], ''The New York Times'', November 19, 1916.</ref>

==Education and college football==
He attended college at [[Princeton University]] where he played [[college football|football]] and competed in [[track and field]]. In track, he won a [[broad jump]]ing championship in the United Kingdom.<ref name=nyt/> In football, he played as a [[quarterback]] and was named a [[1920 College Football All-America Team|consensus All-American]] as a junior in 1920.<ref>"All-America Selections", ''2008 NCAA Division I Football Record Book'', p. 221.</ref> Teammate and fellow All-American [[Stan Keck]] wrote a few years later that the 1920 Princeton<U+2013>[[Yale Bulldogs football|Yale]] game "stands out in my mind as that which offered the most stirring spectacle of my career."<ref name=cfhsn/> Princeton led in the last minute of the first half, 3<U+2013>0, during which they had struggled against their opponent. With the ball on the Yale 40-yard line and only enough time remaining for one play, the Elis assumed that Princeton would attempt a [[field goal (American football)|field goal]]. Keck was set to be the [[placekicker|kicker]] and Lourie the [[holder (American football)|holder]]. When it became apparent Yale would attempt to block the kick, Lourie made an [[audible]] to fake a kick attempt and [[quarterback keeper|run the ball himself]]. Keck threw a [[blocking (American football)|block]] and allowed Lourie to run to the [[end zone]] for a touchdown. Princeton later extended their lead and won, 20<U+2013>0, and finished the season with a 6<U+2013>0<U+2013>1 record.<ref name=cfhsn>[http://docs.google.com/gview?a=v&q=cache:WVsNcJxL30EJ:www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/CFHSN/CFHSNv17/CFHSNv17n2d.pdf+don+lourie&hl=en&gl=us Don Lourie Surprises Yale], ''College Football Historical Society Newsletter'', vol. 17, no. 2, p. 8, [[LA84 Foundation]], retrieved July 17, 2009.</ref> [[Walter Camp]] described Lourie as "the remarkable little general, disclosing every weak point of the opposition."<ref name=hof/>

Lourie missed half of his senior season in 1921 because of an injury.<ref name=hof/> He was awarded the [[Johnny Poe|Poe Memorial Cup]] for services rendered to the team both as a junior and a senior.<ref>[http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9B01EFDF1539E133A25757C0A9679D946095D6CF Poe Memorial Football Cup Is Awarded to Don Lourie], ''The New York Times'', November 4, 1921.</ref><ref name=poe/> Lourie was named to the all-time Princeton team in 1948, and in 1964, the [[National Football Foundation]] bestowed upon him [[National Football Foundation Gold Medal Winners|its Gold Medal]] for lifetime achievement. He was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] in 1974. In his honor, Princeton created the Donold B. Lourie Award, which is awarded annually to the team's most outstanding freshman.<ref name=hof/> Lourie graduated as the [[Class president|president of his class]] in 1922.<ref name=poe>[http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9B04E2DD1638EF3ABC4F52DFB7678389639EDE Lourie Again Awarded Poe Memorial Cup at Princeton], ''The New York Times'', November 17, 1922.</ref> He declined an offer to play for the [[Chicago Bears]] in the fledgling [[National Football League]], and instead, remained at his [[alma mater]] as its [[back (American football)|backfield]] coach.<ref name=nyt/>

==Professional career==
Lourie then went to work for the [[Quaker Oats Company]]. In 1923, he married Mary Edna King with whom he later had a son, Donold K. Lourie who became an attorney, businessman, and novelist.<ref name=nyt/><ref>[http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F04E5DF103AF937A35752C1A96E9C8B63 Paid Notice: Deaths LOURIE, DONOLD K.], ''The New York Times'', November 4, 2008.</ref> He became the president of Quaker Oats in 1947. In 1953, he took a leave of absence from Quaker when President [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] appointed him as the [[Under Secretary of State for Management|Under Secretary of State for Administration]] where Lourie oversaw a reorganization of the department.<ref name=nyt/> He returned to Quaker the following year, and in 1956, he became the [[chief executive officer]], and in 1961, the chairman. At different times, Lourie also acted as director for [[Whitman Corporation|Illinois Central Industries]], the [[International Paper Company]], [[International Harvester]], and the [[Northern Trust Company]]. In 1970, Lourie retired from Quaker and moved to {{city-state|Longwood|Florida}}.<ref name=nyt>[http://www.nytimes.com/1990/01/20/obituaries/donold-lourie-91-a-retired-chairman-of-quaker-oats-co.html Donold Lourie, 91, A Retired Chairman Of Quaker Oats Co.], ''The New York Times'', January 20, 1990.</ref> He died on January 15, 1990 at the age of 90 in {{city-state|Wilmette|Illinois}}.<ref name=hof/>

